1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT REGARDING THE OPERATION OF PUBLIC ENTERPRISES BY THE CITY OF
3 HENDERSONVILLE; TO AUTHORIZE THE TOWN OF MILLS RIVER TO ADOPT A
4 UNIFIED DEVELOPMENT ORDINANCE UNDER CERTAIN CIRCUMSTANCES; TO
5 ALLOW HENDERSON COUNTY TO AMEND ITS ZONING REGULATIONS UNDER
6 CERTAIN CIRCUMSTANCES; TO ELIMINATE THE EXTRATERRITORIAL
7 JURISDICTION AUTHORITY OF MUNICIPALITIES IN HENDERSON COUNTY;
8 AND TO REQUIRE HENDERSON COUNTY TO APPROVE ANY REZONING OF
9 AREAS WITHIN THE COUNTY THAT ARE VOLUNTARILY ANNEXED BY A
10 MUNICIPALITY.
11 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
12
13 PART I. HENDERSONVILLE PUBLIC ENTERPRISE CHANGES
14 SECTION 1.1. G.S. 160A-312 reads as rewritten:
15 "§ 160A-312. Authority to operate public enterprises.
16 (a) A city shall have authority to acquire, construct, establish, enlarge, improve, maintain,
17 own, operate, and contract for the operation of any or all of the public enterprises as defined in
18 this Article to furnish services to the city and its citizens. citizens and other areas and their citizens
19 located outside the corporate limits of the city. Subject to Part 2 of this Article, a city may acquire,
20 construct, establish, enlarge, improve, maintain, own, and operate any public enterprise outside
21 its corporate limits, within reasonable limitations, but in no case shall a city be held liable for
22 damages to those outside the corporate limits for failure to furnish any public enterprise
23 service.limitations.
24 (b) A city shall have full authority to protect and regulate any public enterprise system
25 belonging to or operated by it by adequate and reasonable rules. The rules shall be adopted by
26 ordinance, and shall comply with all of the following:
27 (1) The rules shall apply equally to the public enterprise system both within and
28 outside the corporate limits of the city, and city.
29 (2) The rules may not apply differing treatment within and outside the corporate
30 limits of the city.
31 (3) The rules shall make access to public enterprise services available to the city
32 and its citizens and other areas and their citizens located outside the corporate
33 limits of the city equally.
34 (4) The rules may prioritize the continuation of the provision of services based on
35 availability of excess capacity to provide the service.
*S69-v-3*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (5) The rules may be enforced with the remedies available under any provision of
2 law.
3 …
4 (d) A city shall account for a public enterprise in a separate fund and may not transfer
5 any money from that fund to another except for a capital project fund established for the
6 construction or replacement of assets for that public enterprise. Obligations of the public
7 enterprise may be paid out of the separate fund. Obligations shall not include any other fund or
8 line item in the city's budget."
9 SECTION 1.2. G.S. 160A-31 reads as rewritten:
10 "§ 160A-31. Annexation by petition.
11 (a) The governing board of any municipality may annex by ordinance any area
12 contiguous to its boundaries upon presentation to the governing board of a petition signed by the
13 owners of all the real property located within such area. The petition shall be signed by each
14 owner of real property in the area and shall contain the address of each such owner.owner and a
15 statement that the owner's petition for annexation is not based upon any representation by the
16 municipality that a public enterprise service available outside the corporate limits of that
17 municipality would be withheld from the owner's property without the petition for annexation.
18 …."
19 SECTION 1.3. G.S. 160A-58.1 reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 160A-58.1. Petition for annexation; standards.
21 …
22 (c) The petition shall contain the names, addresses, and signatures of all owners of real
23 property within the proposed satellite corporate limits (except owners not required to sign by
24 subsection (a)), shall describe the area proposed for annexation by metes and bounds, and shall
25 have attached thereto a map showing the area proposed for annexation with relation to the
26 primary corporate limits of the annexing city. The petition shall also contain a statement from
27 the owner that the owner's petition for annexation is not based upon any representation by the
28 municipality that a public enterprise service available outside the corporate limits of that
29 municipality would be withheld from the owner's property without the petition for annexation.
30 When there is any substantial question as to whether the area may be closer to another city than
31 to the annexing city, the map shall also show the area proposed for annexation with relation to
32 the primary corporate limits of the other city. The city council may prescribe the form of the
33 petition.
34 …."
35 SECTION 1.4. This Part applies only to the City of Hendersonville. Section 1.1 of
36 this Part shall not apply to the operation of public transportation systems or off-street parking
37 facilities and systems as public enterprises.
38 SECTION 1.5. This Part becomes effective June 30, 2025. Section 1.1 of this Part
39 applies to the 2025-2026 fiscal year and to each fiscal year thereafter. Any assets, liabilities, or
40 equity of a public enterprise operated or held by the City of Hendersonville in the 2025-2026
41 fiscal year shall be transferred to a separate fund in accordance with G.S. 160A-312, as amended
42 by Section 1.1 of this Part, when this Part becomes law. Sections 1.2 and 1.3 of this Part apply
43 to petitions for annexation received by the City of Hendersonville on or after June 30, 2025.
44
45 PART II. MILLS RIVER UNIFIED DEVELOPMENT ORDINANCE
46 SECTION 2.1.(a) Notwithstanding G.S. 160D-601, as amended by Section 3K.1(a)
47 of S.L. 2024-57, the Town of Mills River may adopt the unified development ordinance as
48 presented to the Town Council in October 2024.
49 SECTION 2.1.(b) This Part is effective when it becomes law, and any adoption of
50 the unified development ordinance shall occur on or before October 1, 2025.
51
Page 2 Senate Bill 69-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 PART III. HENDERSON COUNTY UDO DEFINITIONS
2 SECTION 3.1.(a) Notwithstanding G.S. 160D-601, as amended by Section 3K.1(a)
3 of S.L. 2024-57, Henderson County may amend definitions in its unified development ordinance,
4 not inconsistent with Chapter 160D of the General Statutes, to eliminate or modify uses allowed
5 by right in all zoning districts.
6 SECTION 3.1.(b) This Part is effective when it becomes law, and any amendment
7 of the unified development ordinance shall occur on or before October 1, 2025.
8
9 PART IV. ELIMINATE ETJ IN HENDERSON COUNTY
10 SECTION 4.1.(a) Notwithstanding the provisions of G.S. 160D-202, no
11 municipality in Henderson County shall exercise any of the powers granted to cities under
12 Chapter 160D of the General Statutes or its predecessor, Article 19 of Chapter 160A of the
13 General Statutes, beyond its contiguous corporate limits.
14 SECTION 4.1.(b) The relinquishment of jurisdiction over an area that a municipality
15 in Henderson County is regulating under the authority of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes
16 or its predecessor, Article 19 of Chapter 160A of the General Statutes, shall become effective
17 July 1, 2025.
18 SECTION 4.1.(c) Upon relinquishment of jurisdiction over an area that a
19 municipality in Henderson County is regulating under the authority of Chapter 160D of the
20 General Statutes or its predecessor, Article 19 of Chapter 160A of the General Statutes, the
21 following shall apply:
22 (1) The municipality's regulations and powers of enforcement shall remain in
23 effect until (i) Henderson County has adopted the regulation or (ii) a period of
24 60 days has elapsed following July 1, 2025, the date the relinquishment
25 becomes effective, whichever is sooner. Prior to the transfer of jurisdiction,
26 Henderson County may hold hearings and take other measures consistent with
27 G.S. 160D-204 that may be required in order to adopt and apply its
28 development regulations for the area at the same time it assumes jurisdiction.
29 (2) Any person who has acquired vested rights in a municipality in Henderson
30 County may exercise those rights as if no change of jurisdiction had occurred.
31 Henderson County, in acquiring jurisdiction over the area, may take any action
32 regarding the development approval, certificate, or other evidence of
33 compliance that could have been taken by the municipality pursuant to its
34 development regulations. Except as provided in this subdivision, any building,
35 structure, or other land use in an area over which Henderson County has
36 acquired jurisdiction is subject to the development regulations of Henderson
37 County.
38
39 PART V. HENDERSON COUNTY REZONING APPROVAL
40 SECTION 5.1.(a) If a municipality in Henderson County annexes property under
41 Part 1 or Part 4 of Article 4A of Chapter 160A of the General Statutes, no rezoning under Chapter
42 160D of the General Statutes of any area that includes the annexed property, or any part thereof,
43 may occur without the approval of both the governing body of the municipality and the
44 Henderson County Board of Commissioners.
45 SECTION 5.1.(b) This Part applies only to Henderson County and any municipality
46 located wholly or partly in Henderson County seeking to annex an area located wholly within
47 Henderson County.
48 SECTION 5.1.(c) This Part becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to
49 annexations initiated on or after that date.
50
51 PART VI. EFFECTIVE DATE
